Bob, sit!

30
00:04:05,929 --> 00:04:08,045
Please?

31
00:04:08,209 --> 00:04:10,643
I'm emceeing a lunch in an hour.

32
00:04:10,809 --> 00:04:12,527
Humour me.

33
00:04:12,689 --> 00:04:15,999
-Those the contracts l need to sign?
-Sit!

34
00:04:19,369 --> 00:04:22,167
Your ears would've been
burning this morning.

35
00:04:22,689 --> 00:04:25,487
I had breakfast with
the boys from CBS.

36
00:04:25,649 --> 00:04:27,367
Got something very interesting.

37
00:04:27,529 --> 00:04:30,043
This could be what you're looking for.

38
00:04:31,049 --> 00:04:32,721
-What?
-A television series!

39
00:04:32,889 --> 00:04:36,677
-Goodbye, Lenny.
-Listen to me. Stop running, will you?

40
00:04:36,889 --> 00:04:39,722
I thought you were gonna get me
a Jack Lemmon role.

41
00:04:39,929 --> 00:04:44,286
A feature. It's a critical time for me.
I need something big.

42
00:04:44,449 --> 00:04:46,007
I can be Jack Lemmon.

43
00:04:46,209 --> 00:04:48,803
You are Jack Lemmon.
And Jack Benny.

44
00:04:49,009 --> 00:04:51,079
-Then get me a role.
-That's what this is!

45
00:04:51,249 --> 00:04:54,605
Lemmon and Benny combined.
They want you for the lead.

46
00:04:54,769 --> 00:04:57,329
Just promise me
you'll keep an open mind.

47
00:04:57,489 --> 00:04:59,525
You ready?

48
00:05:00,049 --> 00:05:02,438
It's set in a German prison camp.

49
00:05:04,449 --> 00:05:07,282
-It's a drama?
-No! That-- It's a comedy.

50
00:05:08,049 --> 00:05:09,960
Oh, with the funny Nazis.

51
00:05:11,889 --> 00:05:15,279
-It's a POW camp.
-With a laugh track?

52
00:05:15,449 --> 00:05:19,761
Hey. This is first-class
all the way, my friend.

53
00:05:21,449 --> 00:05:23,519
Bing Crosby Productions doing it.

54
00:05:23,689 --> 00:05:26,123
Sounds like it could be
a career-killer.

55
00:05:33,729 --> 00:05:34,923
Just read it?

56
00:05:37,249 --> 00:05:42,767
He suffered under Pontius Pilate,
was crucified, died and was buried.

57
00:05:42,929 --> 00:05:46,763
He descended to the dead.
On the third day, he rose again.

58
00:05:46,969 --> 00:05:51,599
He ascended into heaven and is
seated at the right hand of the Father.

59
00:05:51,769 --> 00:05:56,559
He will come again to judge
the living and the dead.

60
00:05:56,809 --> 00:06:00,165
-You need a little bit of this.
-There you go, Bobby.

61
00:06:01,009 --> 00:06:04,206
I think it's perfect for me.
I mean this character, Hogan...

62
00:06:04,369 --> 00:06:07,805
...he's quick on his toes,
he's hip, he's a con artist.

63
00:06:07,969 --> 00:06:10,722
I think it's what l've been
working toward my whole career.

64
00:06:10,929 --> 00:06:13,762
You've been working
towards Holocaust comedy?

65
00:06:13,929 --> 00:06:17,478
-Anne!
-What, Bob?

66
00:06:29,169 --> 00:06:31,729
Not in front of the children.
They look up to me.

67
00:06:31,889 --> 00:06:34,801
They're small.
They look up to everyone.

68
00:06:35,569 --> 00:06:39,482
-That's funny. I gotta use that.
-Bob, for 1 5 years...

69
00:06:39,649 --> 00:06:43,881
...l've followed you from job to job.
I'm your number one supporter.

70
00:06:44,049 --> 00:06:47,519
I believe in you. But you expect
me to keep quiet when l see you...

71
00:06:47,689 --> 00:06:51,238
...about to do something
that could ruin your career?

72
00:07:06,449 --> 00:07:08,087
No, not me! Oh, no!

73
00:07:11,089 --> 00:07:13,000
Help! Help!

74
00:07:13,169 --> 00:07:14,761
Those are the riaht words....

75
00:07:14,929 --> 00:07:17,807
All right, honey. You're right.

76
00:07:17,969 --> 00:07:19,288
Family comes first.

77
00:07:19,489 --> 00:07:22,686
I guess it's more important
than some TV show.

78
00:07:22,849 --> 00:07:24,407
You really like the script?

79
00:07:24,569 --> 00:07:27,402
It runs circles around
the other stuff l've been offered.

80
00:07:27,569 --> 00:07:28,763
I know.

81
00:07:28,929 --> 00:07:30,248
I read it.

82
00:07:30,409 --> 00:07:32,365
You did?

83
00:07:34,769 --> 00:07:36,805
It's funny.

84
00:07:37,409 --> 00:07:40,003
Are you saying what
l think you're saying?

85
00:07:41,729 --> 00:07:44,118
You'll quit KNX?

86
00:07:44,369 --> 00:07:47,725
First l'll do both, like we did on
Donna Reed, but if it works....

87
00:07:47,889 --> 00:07:49,607
Well, Donna Reed was part-time.

88
00:07:49,769 --> 00:07:52,841
I just hope l can pull it off.
Hogan's in almost every scene.

89
00:07:53,009 --> 00:07:57,719
You worry. You always worry,
but in the end you succeed.

90
00:07:57,889 --> 00:07:59,766
Easy for you to say.

91
00:08:04,449 --> 00:08:07,919
Hello, Henry.
Now, we're all professionals here.

92
00:08:08,089 --> 00:08:11,525
You've all been working on your
characters, each with his own slant.

93
00:08:11,729 --> 00:08:14,038
We have to keep in mind
this is a gang comedy.

94
00:08:14,209 --> 00:08:17,645
It's funny to the extent the gang
is funny. Like an athletic team.

95
00:08:17,809 --> 00:08:20,277
A great quarterback
without his offensive line...

96
00:08:20,449 --> 00:08:21,848
...ain't gonna complete a pass.

97
00:08:22,009 --> 00:08:24,045
Did you hear about the
Greek quarterback...

98
00:08:24,209 --> 00:08:26,245
...who hated to leave
his buddies behind?

99
00:08:27,649 --> 00:08:29,480
I think we get the point.

100
00:08:30,009 --> 00:08:32,523
Let's pick up with Klink and Hogan.

101
00:08:32,729 --> 00:08:35,721
The great disciplinarian...

102
00:08:35,889 --> 00:08:39,564
...knows when to reward
and when to punish.

103
00:08:39,729 --> 00:08:43,244
Now, my leniency
is a legend, right?

104
00:08:43,409 --> 00:08:46,606
Wrong. You've got a reputation
to uphold, colonel.

105
00:08:46,769 --> 00:08:49,567
You know that. I mean,
you're running the most brutal...

106
00:08:49,729 --> 00:08:51,242
...prison camp in all of Germany!

107
00:08:51,449 --> 00:08:52,438
Okay.

108
00:08:52,609 --> 00:08:55,567
Let's back up.
Bob, don't try so hard.

109
00:08:55,729 --> 00:08:58,243
You're the hero of the show.
It's named after you.

110
00:08:58,409 --> 00:09:02,243
And heroes don't try and be
heroes, they simply are. Okay?

111
00:09:02,409 --> 00:09:04,206
Let's do it again. Same place.

112
00:09:04,369 --> 00:09:07,247
The great disciplinarian knows--

113
00:09:07,449 --> 00:09:11,522
--when to reward and when to punish.
Now, my leniency is a legend, right?

114
00:09:11,729 --> 00:09:13,321
-Wrong.
-What do you mean?

115
00:09:13,489 --> 00:09:15,878
You've got a reputation
to uphold, colonel.

116
00:09:16,089 --> 00:09:18,922
You are running the most brutal
prison camp in all of Germany.

117
00:09:19,089 --> 00:09:21,000
-I am?
-In the world! You're ranked third...

118
00:09:21,169 --> 00:09:23,239
-...behind Devil's lsland and Alcatraz.
-Good.

119
00:09:23,409 --> 00:09:25,161
And you're the toughest
Kommandant.

120
00:09:25,329 --> 00:09:29,641
In the last war it was " Kill the Kaiser."
Today it's " Kill Klink."

121
00:09:29,809 --> 00:09:33,597
" Kill Klink." l like that.

122
00:09:48,929 --> 00:09:51,568
Mel Rosen. I do a little radio show
out of the Quad Cities.

123
00:09:51,729 --> 00:09:54,084
I've actually heard
good things about that.

124
00:09:54,249 --> 00:09:57,605
-Coming from you, that's high praise.
-You gotta give me a tape for that.

125
00:09:57,769 --> 00:09:59,885
-Something to drink?
-A grapefruit juice.

126
00:10:00,049 --> 00:10:03,359
-With vodka?
-No, straight. Last of the straight men.

127
00:10:03,529 --> 00:10:05,838
I'll have another Tom Collins.

128
00:10:06,009 --> 00:10:09,479
Doing a show on the new TV season.
Never pass up one of these junkets.

129
00:10:09,649 --> 00:10:12,527
-Well, l'm with you there.
-So this new show--

130
00:10:12,689 --> 00:10:14,566
I loved you on Donna Reed,
by the way.

131
00:10:14,729 --> 00:10:17,038
It's set in a concentration camp.
A comedy?

132
00:10:17,209 --> 00:10:18,927
Prisoner of war camp.

133
00:10:19,089 --> 00:10:23,560
Yeah, it's got all your typical comedy
elements: Gestapo, police dogs.

134
00:10:23,729 --> 00:10:25,560
So l guess if you
liked World War ll...

135
00:10:25,729 --> 00:10:28,846
...you're gonna love Hoaan's Heroes.

136
00:10:30,849 --> 00:10:35,047
-No, let's not--
-Actually, l got what l want.

137
00:10:35,209 --> 00:10:38,519
Mel, what--?
l thought you were a fellow entertainer.

138
00:10:38,689 --> 00:10:40,839
I'm also a Jew.

139
00:10:41,489 --> 00:10:43,605
It's the same thing.

140
00:10:57,409 --> 00:10:58,398
Thank you.

141
00:10:58,569 --> 00:11:00,560
Are one of those for me?

142
00:11:00,729 --> 00:11:03,402
-Thank you.
-You're welcome.

143
00:11:04,209 --> 00:11:05,961
Bob! Look what l found.

144
00:11:06,129 --> 00:11:07,847
-Hiya.
-Hiya.

145
00:11:08,009 --> 00:11:12,685
This TV reviewer, he just--
I don't mean to offend anybody.

146
00:11:12,849 --> 00:11:14,601
Forget it. Do you see this spread?

147
00:11:14,769 --> 00:11:16,680
Yeah, l gotta hand it to CBS.

148
00:11:16,849 --> 00:11:18,282
They did it for one reason:

149
00:11:18,449 --> 00:11:22,124
The affiliates have seen the pilot.
They love it.

150
00:11:22,289 --> 00:11:25,964
-You play Hogan, don't you?
-I sure do. You want an autograph?

151
00:11:26,129 --> 00:11:29,007
-I've got autographs.
-Darling, you just stop that.

152
00:11:29,169 --> 00:11:31,080
Mr. Crane is a happily married man.

153
00:11:31,249 --> 00:11:36,164
You wanted to see my room, right?
lt's right this way.

154
00:11:38,729 --> 00:11:42,881
Did you catch the radio show
this morning? Guess who was on.

155
00:11:43,529 --> 00:11:46,885
Were you listening?
Johnny Winters.

156
00:11:47,249 --> 00:11:50,764
I swear, he's gotta be the funniest
human being ever born.

157
00:11:52,169 --> 00:11:53,807
Honey?

158
00:12:00,249 --> 00:12:02,046
What's wrong?

159
00:12:08,649 --> 00:12:12,358
Why do we have shady magazines
hidden in our garage?

160
00:12:13,969 --> 00:12:16,483
Those? Those are....

161
00:12:16,649 --> 00:12:20,642
-You know, photography magazines.
-Gent? Cauaht?

162
00:12:21,809 --> 00:12:24,369
I'm a photo nut, Annie, so....

163
00:12:24,529 --> 00:12:27,407
Nature Girls 1965?

164
00:12:29,489 --> 00:12:31,525
They're harmless.

165
00:12:32,489 --> 00:12:35,606
-No wonder you never look at me.
-Would you stop that?

166
00:12:35,769 --> 00:12:41,526
Listen, l'm out the door every morning
at 5:30. I'm not home until after dark.

167
00:12:41,689 --> 00:12:44,123
You see how hard l'm working?

168
00:12:45,969 --> 00:12:50,679
-Are you seeing another woman?
-Absolutely not.

169
00:12:52,569 --> 00:12:55,083
I want those magazines
out of the house.

170
00:12:55,249 --> 00:12:58,286
Yeah, l'll throw them away.

171
00:12:58,449 --> 00:13:02,601
-I've seen them before. I just ignored it.
-All right, l get the message.

172
00:13:02,769 --> 00:13:06,159
Bad enough l've gotta hide them
like some teenager.

173
00:13:06,329 --> 00:13:08,126
Well, what did you have in mind?

174
00:13:08,289 --> 00:13:10,928
Putting them on the coffee table
for our guests to see?

175
00:13:11,089 --> 00:13:12,647
I apologize.

176
00:13:12,809 --> 00:13:16,518
-Maybe we should see Father Donnelly.
-No, it's our business.

177
00:13:16,689 --> 00:13:19,408
Family business.
We'll keep it at home.

178
00:13:19,569 --> 00:13:23,244
You're never home. I just thought
when you started shooting Hoaan's...

179
00:13:23,409 --> 00:13:29,041
-...that this would change things.
-It will, darling. Trust me. It will.

180
00:13:30,649 --> 00:13:33,607
Hogan's Heroes premiered
September 1 7, 1965...

181
00:13:33,769 --> 00:13:35,600
...8.:30 on Friday niaht.

182
00:13:35,769 --> 00:13:37,964
When the Nielsen ratinas
were released...

183
00:13:38,129 --> 00:13:41,644
... Hogan's, out of 98 prime-time shows,
finished number five.

184
00:13:41,809 --> 00:13:44,369
Of the new shows,
it was number one.

185
00:13:44,529 --> 00:13:46,918
I've always had
an extraordinary amount of luck.

186
00:13:47,089 --> 00:13:49,239
Beina in the riaht place
at the riaht time.

187
00:13:49,409 --> 00:13:52,958
There was some controversy
the first few months, but it died away.

188
00:13:53,129 --> 00:13:55,882
Mondays we blocked the show.
Tuesdays we did exteriors.

189
00:13:56,049 --> 00:13:58,438
Wednesdays and Thursdays
we did interiors.

190
00:13:58,609 --> 00:14:01,487
Friday we'd have a table readina
of the next week's script.

191
00:14:01,649 --> 00:14:04,959
Weekends we called each other
and went over everythina. I loved it.

192
00:14:05,129 --> 00:14:09,407
Give me a vacation,
and three days later l'm aoina crazy.

193
00:14:12,329 --> 00:14:13,728
Not another power outage.

194
00:14:13,889 --> 00:14:17,165
No, sir. I'm installing Richard's
new high-fidelity unit.

195
00:14:17,329 --> 00:14:20,560
-In his trailer here?
-I can wire anything.

196
00:14:20,729 --> 00:14:23,402
-Yeah?
-You got a second?

197
00:14:23,569 --> 00:14:25,799
Let me show you something.

198
00:14:30,289 --> 00:14:32,723
I designed this myself. Listen.

199
00:14:38,769 --> 00:14:40,361
Pretty groovy, huh?

200
00:14:41,289 --> 00:14:44,361
-I'm Bob Crane.
-John. John Carpenter.

201
00:14:53,609 --> 00:14:56,077
Well, l've never been much into hi-fi.

202
00:14:56,249 --> 00:14:58,717
-Photography's always been my thing.
-I'm with you.

203
00:14:58,889 --> 00:15:01,483
If you like photography,
you'll love VTRs.

204
00:15:01,649 --> 00:15:03,526
-"VTRs"?
-Videotape recorders.

205
00:15:03,689 --> 00:15:08,843
Magnetic coding, like audio tape.
Same principle, only with pictures.

206
00:15:09,009 --> 00:15:12,126
Sony, Ampex, Panasonic,
they're all developing VTRs.

207
00:15:12,289 --> 00:15:14,928
-Hi, Bob.
-Hey, Robert. So this is like your...?

208
00:15:15,089 --> 00:15:17,683
I sort of freelance.
I work with Sonycom from Japan...

209
00:15:17,849 --> 00:15:20,682
...helping them introduce
helical-scan VTRs.

210
00:15:20,849 --> 00:15:23,488
I sold Dawson the third VTR
in the U.S.

211
00:15:23,649 --> 00:15:27,244
-Sold one to LBJ, Elvis.
-Yeah?

212
00:15:27,409 --> 00:15:31,038
Showed him how to use it. Nice cat.

213
00:15:31,729 --> 00:15:33,799
Back in 1 5 minutes, Bob.

214
00:15:33,969 --> 00:15:36,688
Shoot, gotta run.

215
00:15:36,849 --> 00:15:38,680
-Nice meeting you.
-All right.

216
00:15:38,849 --> 00:15:40,601
Carpenter.

217
00:15:41,889 --> 00:15:44,357
-" FBl."
-Full-blooded lndian.

218
00:15:44,529 --> 00:15:50,445
Well, actually, half-blooded.
Here, take my card.

219
00:15:50,609 --> 00:15:53,123
Dawson and l are hooking up
over at Salome's later...

220
00:15:53,289 --> 00:15:55,439
...if you want to come and join us.

221
00:15:55,609 --> 00:15:59,568
-I actually prom--
-You'd like it. It's a nice joint.

222
00:15:59,729 --> 00:16:01,959
-House band. Strippers.
-Well....

223
00:16:02,129 --> 00:16:04,120
Hey, mate. How's it coming?

224
00:16:04,289 --> 00:16:07,361
You're all set up, big daddy.
Eight watts of pumping power.

225
00:16:07,529 --> 00:16:12,319
Hear that? l just got
the best bloody hi-fi on this lot.

226
00:16:13,009 --> 00:16:14,761
I gotta run.

227
00:16:14,929 --> 00:16:16,567
Salome's.

228
00:16:46,129 --> 00:16:49,326
-Colonel! How's it hanging?
-Can't complain.

229
00:16:49,489 --> 00:16:51,241
Glad you could make it.

230
00:16:51,409 --> 00:16:54,845
Richard. I brought you
a call sheet for tomorrow.

231
00:16:55,009 --> 00:16:59,241
I already got one.
Let me get you something to drink.

232
00:17:00,209 --> 00:17:05,044
-I'll have a grapefruit juice.
